WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.800
So in this second table, we're going to go through a few things, and it's going to introduce a pretty large concept called units notation.

00:00:06.800 --> 00:00:14.300
The table we're going to make is going to be full of units, but let's show you why we use units at all.

00:00:14.300 --> 00:00:19.400
It's because tables are often full of values, and we need to know what those values actually signify.

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:24.700
So it's common to provide measurement units of values within the table.

00:00:24.700 --> 00:00:28.700
And we see this both in tables and also in plots. You may see these in plot axes.

00:00:28.700 --> 00:00:35.400
You see the name of the axis and also the units that the values are represented as.

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:38.200
A table is really no different. So let's take a look at a few examples.

00:00:38.200 --> 00:00:43.099
So in this table, we have running down this column of the column called units.

00:00:43.099 --> 00:00:50.599
We have basically inline units, copies of per milliliter. We have micromoles per liter.

00:00:50.599 --> 00:00:55.700
These are somewhat complex to write in general.

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:59.700
So we make it a bit easier with units notation, especially this right here.

00:00:59.700 --> 00:01:08.000
We have things like exponentiated values like minus two or two or even degrees n and degrees w.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.699
Not so easy to type in, but units notation really helps with that sort of thing.

00:01:12.699 --> 00:01:19.900
And this is another type of units where it's inline and we have inverse unit values with minus one.

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:24.000
And we see that quite a bit. So this would be joules per mole per K.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:29.099
And we have a way to do that quite easily with units notation.

00:01:29.099 --> 00:01:32.699
So in grid tables, units notation, it helps you create inline units.

00:01:32.699 --> 00:01:35.699
So let's try quickly to understand this specialized syntax.

00:01:35.699 --> 00:01:38.599
First of all, we need to identify what is in units notation.

00:01:38.599 --> 00:01:41.800
We do that with the double curly braces on each side.

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:44.800
So it's sort of bracketing what are the units.

00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:51.500
And then the different spaces separate the different units, which is part of the whole unit, essentially.

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:54.099
And then each of the different parts is formatted.

00:01:54.099 --> 00:01:59.300
And we see right here that we have a name of the unit and then we have the exponent part.

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:06.000
And so centimeters cubed, we use the caret three and it gets rendered as centimeters cubed.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:07.800
Same goes with inverse seconds.

00:02:07.800 --> 00:02:14.899
We have the name, which is S and then like a caret minus one to create that superscripted part.

00:02:14.899 --> 00:02:19.300
If you want more guidance on units in general, you can check out this NIST website, physics.nist.gov.

00:02:19.300 --> 00:02:23.000
There's a checklist on expressing units there.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.399
Inside the documentation for grid tables, we have a basic guide to units notation.

00:02:27.399 --> 00:02:36.600
And of course, it's a table and we have several rules for how to build up a unit or set of units using this notation.

00:02:36.699 --> 00:02:40.300
And we have a number of example inputs which sort of show the rule.

00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:45.100
And then we see the output, essentially, which is the formatted unit itself.

00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:46.800
So quite a few things to gather here.

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:51.000
We have things like ways to italicize and bold the text.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:57.300
We have ways to insert different glyphs, which are hard to type in, like per mil, for instance.

00:02:57.300 --> 00:03:00.800
We can show chemistry by surrounding with percent signs.

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:07.300
And we have different ways of showing a subscript and a superscript typeset in different ways.

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:09.600
So we can experiment with units notation.

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:14.399
Inside the package, we just have to import from grid tables the define units function.

00:03:14.399 --> 00:03:20.899
And if you play with that in Notebook, we can just use define units and then put a piece of text in units notation.

00:03:20.899 --> 00:03:26.800
And in the output, you'll have a formatted HTML representation of the units.

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:30.399
So we're going to try that in the Notebook a bit later.

00:03:30.399 --> 00:03:38.000
But for now, we'll talk about formatting for science with format units and the format scientific methods.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:44.199
So we have a huge collection of format methods, and they all begin with fmt underscore.

00:03:44.199 --> 00:03:46.699
We will use two of them here, format units.

00:03:46.699 --> 00:03:52.500
And these can take in chemical formula text between percent signs and properly format those.

00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:59.899
So for instance, this H202 will just become H202 where the two values are subscripted.

00:03:59.899 --> 00:04:06.300
Format scientific is really good for large or really small values, and it puts them in scientific notation,

00:04:06.300 --> 00:04:14.600
which is what you often see within lots of places where you represent small or very large numbers.

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:18.399
And the cool thing it does is that if the number is in the range of like 1 to 10,

00:04:18.399 --> 00:04:25.000
it doesn't include a times 10 to the 0 part because the convention is to avoid null exponents.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:29.399
So that is just essentially rounded.

00:04:29.399 --> 00:04:33.299
Another thing we can do is in a table, we sometimes have missing values.

00:04:33.299 --> 00:04:36.600
They show up as none most of the time.

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:39.700
But we can replace that with different bits of text.

00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:41.700
So we can use a submissing method.

00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:47.100
It has a columns argument, and by default, it will target all the columns in a table.

00:04:47.100 --> 00:04:52.399
So if you just use submissing by itself on the example table, which has lots of missing values,

00:04:52.399 --> 00:04:58.000
it will replace any none text with a long dash, which is called mdash.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.200
And you can specify some other bit of text that you want as well.

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:06.700
Like, for instance, say you want the missing text to be missing, the word missing.

00:05:06.700 --> 00:05:14.700
That can be done, and you see within this table that anything that was none is now has the text missing.

00:05:14.700 --> 00:05:22.100
Another thing you can do, which is great, if you want to hide certain columns from the final output,

00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:25.500
there's actually a method for that called calls hide.

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:26.799
So why would you even do this?

00:05:26.799 --> 00:05:31.399
Maybe sometimes in a table you might use an expression which takes a value from a column,

00:05:31.399 --> 00:05:35.799
but you don't necessarily want to show that column because it's not very suitable for display.

00:05:35.799 --> 00:05:39.500
You can hide those columns and use the calls hide method for that.

00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:47.399
And in this case, you just provide a single column or a list of columns to not show in the final table.

00:05:47.799 --> 00:05:57.399
And that's shown in the code along with that file name, PyReactionsTable.qmd.

00:05:57.399 --> 00:06:02.100
Also within grade tables, we have a large number of opt underscore methods,

00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:06.299
and these give you an opportunity to quickly style the table in different ways.

00:06:06.299 --> 00:06:12.500
So we can style the table very quickly by using opt stylize, even without any arguments.

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:17.899
It'll take this pretty boring default table and apply a theme throughout.

00:06:17.899 --> 00:06:21.500
So now we notice if we use this, we have some blue.

00:06:21.500 --> 00:06:28.100
We have some blue lines and we have blue background color in the stub.

00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:32.700
And there's lots of options within that method.

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:37.200
There's like six style options and also six color treatments.

00:06:37.200 --> 00:06:40.799
So any combination of those will give you a radically different looking table.

00:06:40.799 --> 00:06:45.200
So you can experiment with those.

00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:52.500
And another thing you do is you can change the font for the entire table really quickly with the opt table font method.

00:06:52.500 --> 00:06:57.399
In this case, we're taking the input table, which applies a default font,

00:06:57.399 --> 00:06:59.500
but we can change that to Times New Roman.

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:06.700
And in doing so, we see that every bit of text on the table is changed to that typeface.

00:07:06.700 --> 00:07:13.399
Aside from that, you could apply a stack, which is a theme set of fonts that work well across systems.

00:07:13.399 --> 00:07:17.600
So with opt table font, we could use the stack argument.

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:19.399
And there's a number of keywords that work with that.

00:07:19.399 --> 00:07:21.299
In this case, I'm using humanist.

00:07:21.299 --> 00:07:26.799
And what it does is it just chooses like a family of fonts which work well across different systems.

00:07:26.799 --> 00:07:28.700
So in this case, it provides a humanist look.

00:07:28.700 --> 00:07:32.399
If you know all about typefaces, you'll know a bit about this.

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:40.200
But the idea here is that you just choose a keyword, and it works across different types of OSs and different platforms.

00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:43.799
So there's many different stack types, and these are just a number of keywords.

00:07:43.799 --> 00:07:45.500
So you can choose monospace fonts.

00:07:45.500 --> 00:07:49.399
You can choose things which are script or handwritten.

00:07:49.399 --> 00:07:56.899
And there's lots of information about these in the help docs for system underscore fonts.

00:07:56.899 --> 00:08:01.799
Sometimes what you want to do a lot is change the amount of space that a table takes up.

00:08:01.799 --> 00:08:06.500
And to do that, you usually want to change the padding in a table.

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:08.299
So there's actually two methods for this.

00:08:08.299 --> 00:08:12.200
One is called opt vertical padding.

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:13.799
And this takes a scale argument.

00:08:13.799 --> 00:08:19.100
Anything below 1 means you're shrinking the table or sort of like reducing the amount of vertical space.

00:08:19.100 --> 00:08:24.100
If you go above 1, anywhere between 1 and 3, you're actually increasing the height of the table

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:28.299
because you're actually increasing the vertical padding.

00:08:28.299 --> 00:08:29.399
There's another one.

00:08:29.399 --> 00:08:32.500
So basically the analog of this is opt horizontal padding.

00:08:32.500 --> 00:08:38.799
In this case, you're either compressing the table or expanding it in the horizontal direction.

00:08:38.799 --> 00:08:44.099
So in this case, I'm taking this table right here in the bottom left, applying a pretty large scale value,

00:08:44.099 --> 00:08:52.099
and what it's doing is it's expanding the table both left and right.

