they'd be really small values.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:01.599
These are like 10 to the minus 11,

00:17:01.599 --> 00:17:04.199
so much better in scientific notation.

00:17:04.199 --> 00:17:07.099
And that's really usually what you see.

00:17:07.099 --> 00:17:09.000
So we have a lot of none values here.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:12.099
These are essentially missing values in the table.

00:17:12.099 --> 00:17:15.900
We really don't want to see none written many times.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:19.699
We can choose something better than that to replace it.

00:17:19.699 --> 00:17:23.400
And to do that, we use submissing.

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:29.800
Okay. And what we're doing here is we're going to select the columns,

00:17:29.800 --> 00:17:38.099
which just basically end in K298 as before, like so.

00:17:38.099 --> 00:17:40.800
Okay, if I run this without anything else,

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:46.599
the default replacement text will be this M dash, a long dash essentially.

00:17:46.599 --> 00:17:48.500
Yeah, so we see that all the way down.

00:17:48.500 --> 00:17:55.599
It could be a nicer way to flag a missing value compared to just having none.

00:17:55.599 --> 00:18:00.099
But one thing also I see in this table is that we have an 03 column

00:18:00.099 --> 00:18:02.699
with no data in it whatsoever.

00:18:02.699 --> 00:18:05.099
This may be fine, but I think in this particular table,

00:18:05.099 --> 00:18:08.699
I'd rather just get rid of that column altogether.

00:18:08.699 --> 00:18:13.000
And we can do that inside the Green Tables API.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:18.900
And to do it, we would just have to use the calls hide method.

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:20.199
Great.

00:18:20.199 --> 00:18:24.099
And we just specify the single column that we want to hide.

00:18:24.099 --> 00:18:30.199
So in columns, it's just going to be 03 underscore K298

00:18:30.199 --> 00:18:33.599
because I remembered what column name that was.

00:18:33.599 --> 00:18:37.199
And then I'm going to run that cell and it's just gone.

00:18:37.300 --> 00:18:41.099
So we're hiding it at the very end, right, essentially.

00:18:41.099 --> 00:18:42.900
We didn't have to hide it.

00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:48.099
We didn't have to omit that column initially when we worked with the table

00:18:48.099 --> 00:18:52.800
using our pollers data frame manipulation methods.

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:54.900
We just did it right here because you can change your mind

00:18:54.900 --> 00:19:00.800
and just unhide it or not hide it at all, which is great.

00:19:00.800 --> 00:19:03.500
And now we want to move ahead to some styling

00:19:03.500 --> 00:19:05.099
because I believe that the table looks pretty good

00:19:05.099 --> 00:19:07.699
in terms of formatting and structuring.

00:19:07.699 --> 00:19:11.599
So the last few things that remain are a little bit of styling for this table.

00:19:11.599 --> 00:19:14.800
So let's do that with opt stylize.

00:19:14.800 --> 00:19:18.099
We're going to use a number of opt methods to do some quick styling.

00:19:18.099 --> 00:19:24.900
So opt stylize gives us a few styling themes

00:19:24.900 --> 00:19:26.599
and we can just use it as it is.

00:19:26.599 --> 00:19:29.599
So I'll run the cell and there it is.

00:19:29.599 --> 00:19:33.800
But within opt stylize, there's actually a number of different styles

00:19:33.800 --> 00:19:36.500
from one to six, they're numbered.

00:19:36.500 --> 00:19:38.699
And we also have a number of colors that you can use.

00:19:38.699 --> 00:19:40.599
And these are named colors.

00:19:40.599 --> 00:19:44.800
The best way to find out what these are is to look at the opt stylize documentation

00:19:44.800 --> 00:19:47.199
either through the API reference.

00:19:47.199 --> 00:19:49.400
You can sort of get it if you hover over it.

00:19:49.400 --> 00:19:53.099
You can see what is in the color part of the docs here.

00:19:53.099 --> 00:19:56.900
So it seems to be like blue, cyan, pink, green, red, and gray.

00:19:56.900 --> 00:20:00.199
So by default it's blue and that's what we see here.

00:20:00.199 --> 00:20:02.599
So it looks pretty good to me.

00:20:02.599 --> 00:20:04.300
What doesn't look good to me is a default font.

00:20:04.300 --> 00:20:06.099
So let's change that.

00:20:06.099 --> 00:20:12.199
We can change the font for the entire table with the opt table font method.

00:20:12.199 --> 00:20:13.900
Okay, so we're going to do that.

00:20:13.900 --> 00:20:18.500
And just as an extra thing, we don't have to choose a font that exists on our system.

00:20:18.500 --> 00:20:25.800
We have a little extra thing called system fonts like that.

00:20:25.800 --> 00:20:31.599
And that's a helper function that lets us use a set of themed stacks of fonts.

00:20:31.599 --> 00:20:36.699
Okay, so they take a different name depending on which one you use.

00:20:36.699 --> 00:20:40.900
You can think of this as like a font theme that works across different systems.

00:20:40.900 --> 00:20:44.900
The only thing we have to do is import that helper function.

00:20:44.900 --> 00:20:51.599
So from grade tables import system fonts.

00:20:51.599 --> 00:20:52.400
Great.

00:20:52.400 --> 00:20:54.599
So there's a number of different names here.

00:20:54.599 --> 00:20:58.900
We have things like system UI, which is the default, transitional, old style.

00:20:58.900 --> 00:21:00.699
Humanist is what I'm using.

00:21:00.699 --> 00:21:03.900
It just shows that it's taking this font family right here.

00:21:03.900 --> 00:21:06.000
So it's pretty resilient in moving across systems.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:10.400
Or say you're running on a Linux system, it should work,

00:21:10.400 --> 00:21:12.000
provide you something very similar.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:17.199
If you're on a phone, again, this should give you a font which is of that certain theme.

00:21:17.199 --> 00:21:18.800
So I'm going to run this.

00:21:18.800 --> 00:21:21.000
And we see that the font did change.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:24.400
The table width changed a little bit because the font is a little bit thinner.

00:21:24.400 --> 00:21:27.800
But we see we no longer have that default font in our table.

00:21:27.800 --> 00:21:31.400
It's all been changed for every bit of text on the table.

00:21:31.400 --> 00:21:31.900
Okay.

00:21:31.900 --> 00:21:39.300
And speaking of spacing, if you find that the table is a bit too scrunched in

00:21:39.300 --> 00:21:42.699
or there's not enough space for it to breathe, you can change that.

00:21:42.699 --> 00:21:44.599
And there's two opt methods for that.

00:21:44.599 --> 00:21:48.500
We have opt horizontal padding, which is what we'll use here.

00:21:48.500 --> 00:21:51.500
And it takes a scale argument.

00:21:51.500 --> 00:21:54.900
And what you do with that argument is you just change the amount of space.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:58.000
If you have a positive or if you have a value above one,

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:03.199
it increases the amount of vertical space or padding on the left or right sides of each cell.

00:22:03.199 --> 00:22:05.400
So let's actually pump that up to three.

00:22:05.400 --> 00:22:07.900
And we'll check out the effect of that.

00:22:07.900 --> 00:22:08.400
There we go.

00:22:08.400 --> 00:22:10.900
So you can see the table is a bit wider than before.

00:22:10.900 --> 00:22:14.099
And we just have a little more space between the neighboring columns for the values.

00:22:14.099 --> 00:22:17.900
So they're not so encroached on each other.

00:22:17.900 --> 00:22:21.900
And that is basically the entire table here.

